questions.question:
Consider the relation scheme R = {E, F, G, H, I, J, K, L, M, N} and the set of functional dependencies
{ {E,F} -> {G},  {F} -> {I,J},  {E,H} -> {K,L},  {K} -> {M},  {L} -> {N} }
on R. What is the key for R?
A. {E,F}
B. {E,F,H}
C. {E,F,H,I}
D. {E}

steps.apply:
Start: {E,F,H}
Apply {E,F}->G: add G => {E,F,G,H}
Apply {F}->I,J: add I,J => {E,F,G,H,I,J}
Apply {E,H}->K,L: add K,L => {E,F,G,H,I,J,K,L}
Apply {K}->M: add M => {E,F,G,H,I,J,K,L,M}
Apply {L}->N: add N => {E,F,G,H,I,J,K,L,M,N}
This equals all 10 attributes of R, so {E,F,H} is a superkey.

questions.question:
Consider the relation X(P, Q, R, S, T, U) with the following set of functional dependencies
F = { {P,R} -> {S,T},  {P,S} -> U,  {Q,R} -> {P,H} }
Which of the following is the trivial functional dependency in F^+, where F^+ is closure to F?
A. {P,R} -> {S,T}
B. {P,B} -> {R,T}
C. {P,Q,S} -> {Q,S}
D. {P,Q,R} -> {S,T,U}
